Energy for Curvilinear One-Dimensional Systems

It is possible for the path of an object to be nonlinear, but still one-dimensional. For example, a curved track can be described with a single parameter, say the distance from the origin . The speed of the object along the track is easily seen to be and its kinetic energy is therefore just

The force on the object traveling such a track is a little more complicated. Since the track is curved, the normal force is not always zero. On the contrary, the normal force is what constrains the object to follow the path (which is why the normal force is called the force of constraint). Since the normal force does no work, as it is perpendicular to the displacement, it is the tangential component of the net force that we are concerned with. It's easy to show (4.32) that
If all forces with tangential components are conservative then we can define a potential energy such that and the total mechanical energy is constant.

Examples


Consider a cube balancing on a rubber cylinder. The cube does not slip on the cylinder. This is an example of a one dimensional system. The position of the cube can be described with just the angle . The two constraining forces are the normal and frictional forces of the cylinder on the cube. The normal force doesn't do work as it is always perpendicular to the motion. In this case, the frictional force doesn't do work either as the cube is not dragging along the cylinder. Thus, the only force here is gravity. Since gravity is conservative and gravitational potential energy is the same as for a point mass at the center of the cube, that is where is the height of above the origin.
